The characters showed promise, but they

244
00:13:01,800 --> 00:13:02,600
didn't have a lot of depth.

245
00:13:03,040 --> 00:13:04,261
In fact, if you play the first game,

246
00:13:04,281 --> 00:13:05,921
you'll notice that Ratchet was kind of a jerk.

247
00:13:06,161 --> 00:13:08,562
He was too sarcastic, too snarky, too selfish.

248
00:13:09,042 --> 00:13:10,743
So for the next game, we recast Ratchet

249
00:13:10,763 --> 00:13:12,763
with James Arnold Taylor, and we rewrote him

250
00:13:12,823 --> 00:13:14,724
to be a kinder, more curious character.

251
00:13:15,030 --> 00:13:17,191
with a sense of humor that didn't require putting others down.

252
00:13:17,551 --> 00:13:21,654
So thanks to that first Ratchet game, Insomniac learned a basic but important lesson.

253
00:13:24,375 --> 00:13:27,817
Make the time to develop your heroes and their relationships.

254
00:13:28,738 --> 00:13:33,080
In game design, it's very easy to get laser focused on the game because the natural inclination

255
00:13:33,100 --> 00:13:35,181
is to say, hey, we have to make the game work before anything else.

256
00:13:35,582 --> 00:13:38,784
But your audience is not going to care about your heroes if they don't care about their

257
00:13:38,844 --> 00:13:39,564
place in the world.

258
00:13:42,215 --> 00:13:44,737
So over the next two sequels, we refined the franchise.

259
00:13:44,877 --> 00:13:46,839
On Going Commando, we fully embraced the weapons

260
00:13:47,279 --> 00:13:49,861
for our gameplay strategy and added RPG elements.

261
00:13:50,681 --> 00:13:52,363
We had a lot of variety in this game

262
00:13:52,383 --> 00:13:53,644
in the form of mega games.

263
00:13:54,504 --> 00:13:56,606
We included this battle arena that really let people

264
00:13:56,706 --> 00:13:59,648
test out their weapons and encourage people to buy weapons

265
00:13:59,688 --> 00:14:01,890
and try them out in these really cool spaces.

266
00:14:03,411 --> 00:14:05,552
We also had these new tiny planets

267
00:14:05,632 --> 00:14:07,013
that we called Spherical Worlds.

268
00:14:07,033 --> 00:14:08,655
This was actually something that we had prototyped

269
00:14:08,675 --> 00:14:10,236
for the original Ratchet and Clank.

270
00:14:10,256 --> 00:14:10,556
We had them.

271
00:14:11,044 --> 00:14:12,345
Flying around one on a hoverboard,

272
00:14:12,385 --> 00:14:14,046
but we just realized we couldn't do it in time,

273
00:14:14,127 --> 00:14:15,768
so we saved that idea for this game.

274
00:14:17,109 --> 00:14:21,092
We had hover bike races and space combat missions too.

275
00:14:21,112 --> 00:14:24,235
Now players appreciated the huge leap forward

276
00:14:24,275 --> 00:14:25,756
in terms of gameplay depth and breadth.

277
00:14:26,076 --> 00:14:28,318
They also loved the double entendre of go and commando,

278
00:14:28,338 --> 00:14:30,419
because not a lot of stylized franchises

279
00:14:30,820 --> 00:14:31,861
could be so subversive.

280
00:14:32,221 --> 00:14:34,122
So we decided to embrace that going forward,

281
00:14:34,162 --> 00:14:36,224
and another Ratchet and Clank tradition was born.

282
00:14:36,799 --> 00:14:38,640
Yeah, when they pitched going commando to me,

283
00:14:38,680 --> 00:14:39,841
I didn't know what that meant.

284
00:14:40,461 --> 00:14:44,364
Sounds good, yeah, okay.

285
00:14:44,384 --> 00:14:47,366
Okay, so that leads us to, of course, Up Your Arsenal.

286
00:14:48,527 --> 00:14:50,629
Okay, so in that game, we introduced multiplayer,

287
00:14:50,709 --> 00:14:51,770
single-player battlefields,

288
00:14:51,950 --> 00:14:55,793
and our most iconic villain of the series, Dr. Nefarious.

289
00:14:56,533 --> 00:14:59,435
He was inspired by old-school sci-fi B-movies

290
00:14:59,495 --> 00:15:02,037
and quickly became our most recognizable super villain.

291
00:15:03,658 --> 00:15:06,260
Up Your Arsenal was a huge hit with players and critics

292
00:15:06,563 --> 00:15:08,985
Looking back, there were a lot of key elements that made it successful.

293
00:15:09,365 --> 00:15:11,127
Ratchet and Clank had a textured relationship.

294
00:15:11,167 --> 00:15:13,849
They bantered, they disagreed, but you could always tell these guys were buddies.

295
00:15:14,289 --> 00:15:16,631
We had outrageous weapons with badass upgrades.

296
00:15:17,032 --> 00:15:18,593
There were gadgets and planet hopping.

297
00:15:18,633 --> 00:15:19,994
We had tons of Captain Quark.

298
00:15:20,415 --> 00:15:23,477
The visuals were stylized with rich detail and a vibrant palette.

299
00:15:23,778 --> 00:15:28,141
It had a Douglas Adams-inspired humor that I love so much and a great balance of platforming

300
00:15:28,161 --> 00:15:28,522
to shooting.

301
00:15:30,807 --> 00:15:34,729
But yet this was around this time where we suddenly started to see mascot characters

302
00:15:34,889 --> 00:15:39,291
like fading away or they were kind of putting on the back shelf until later.

303
00:15:40,632 --> 00:15:42,513
And they started to go into hibernation.

304
00:15:43,433 --> 00:15:48,556
But we believe that part of the reason why the Ratchet & Clank series endured was that

305
00:15:48,656 --> 00:15:50,637
we dramatically evolved it.

306
00:15:51,618 --> 00:15:56,360
We transformed it from being a platformer with shooting to a shooter with platforming.

307
00:15:57,518 --> 00:15:59,938
So we had seen that people were very receptive to the guns,

308
00:16:00,239 --> 00:16:02,079
and we've really integrated that.

309
00:16:02,239 --> 00:16:06,580
And by the third game, we had full circle strafing

310
00:16:06,600 --> 00:16:08,681
with R1 trigger and really made this

311
00:16:08,721 --> 00:16:12,762
into a modern-day third-person shooter in terms of mechanics.

312
00:16:13,662 --> 00:16:16,823
So the big lesson here was we really had to adapt or die.

313
00:16:17,963 --> 00:16:20,484
It's really important to listen to what players want to play.

314
00:16:20,964 --> 00:16:22,884
But then, of course, you're having

315
00:16:22,904 --> 00:16:26,005
to watch the market trends and learn

316
00:16:26,045 --> 00:16:27,025
what other games are doing.

317
00:16:28,004 --> 00:16:31,847
But then you also want to amplify what's great about your own game and what makes it stand out

318
00:16:31,987 --> 00:16:34,028
So there's definitely a tricky balance there

319
00:16:35,108 --> 00:16:39,451
so we really thought we'd hit our stride with up your arsenal, but we started to face a

320
00:16:40,492 --> 00:16:42,953
small obstacle here and

321
00:16:42,993 --> 00:16:45,154
That is the fourth game slump

322
00:16:46,435 --> 00:16:46,695
so

323
00:16:47,616 --> 00:16:49,017
Really what that is is that?

324
00:16:49,634 --> 00:16:57,377
This happens all the time with movies and trilogies where you feel like you've said all that you could say with the third game, you nail it, and then you're like, oh, people want more.

325
00:16:57,417 --> 00:17:00,298
We have the opportunity to make another game that people want to play, but what do we do?

326
00:17:01,338 --> 00:17:04,640
So, you know, again, it's like that rule of threes.

327
00:17:05,080 --> 00:17:09,661
And we were concerned, too, that we'd made these three games back to back one year after the next.

328
00:17:10,362 --> 00:17:11,742
And what do people want with the fourth game?

329
00:17:11,782 --> 00:17:12,782
Are they starting to get tired?

330
00:17:13,543 --> 00:17:17,184
And is there some level of franchise fatigue happening here?

331
00:17:17,853 --> 00:17:20,695
So the question was, well, maybe we need to adapt further.

332
00:17:20,755 --> 00:17:23,457
Maybe with Up Your Arsenal, we made it a third person,

333
00:17:24,217 --> 00:17:26,959
modern shooter, but how can we take this even further?

334
00:17:27,499 --> 00:17:29,981
And we were looking at other games that were really big.

335
00:17:30,001 --> 00:17:33,023
We were looking at, I don't know, your GTAs

336
00:17:33,103 --> 00:17:33,903
and stuff like that.

337
00:17:34,884 --> 00:17:36,945
And we had a little bit of envy, like,

338
00:17:37,285 --> 00:17:37,946
what can we do there?

339
00:17:38,086 --> 00:17:41,288
So at the time, for us, it was Halo.

340
00:17:41,308 --> 00:17:41,588
I know.

341
00:17:41,608 --> 00:17:44,210
So in 2005, we went dark.

342
00:17:50,132 --> 00:17:53,253
And right off the bat, you're going to notice that we dropped the double entendre.

343
00:17:53,853 --> 00:17:55,414
We even took Clank's name off the title.

344
00:17:55,714 --> 00:17:58,614
In hindsight, we've got to acknowledge that was kind of not cool.

345
00:18:00,935 --> 00:18:03,116
While other co-op multiplayer features were strong,

346
00:18:03,496 --> 00:18:05,296
it was still a big departure from the franchise.

347
00:18:05,376 --> 00:18:07,117
We removed fan favorite Captain Quark,

348
00:18:07,317 --> 00:18:08,377
we sidelined Clank,

349
00:18:08,817 --> 00:18:10,158
and lost the exploration factor.

350
00:18:10,478 --> 00:18:12,078
Instead, we sent Ratchet to various planets

351
00:18:12,118 --> 00:18:14,539
simply to survive a Running Man-style game show.

352
00:18:14,879 --> 00:18:15,619
It was a fun game.

353
00:18:16,072 --> 00:18:17,293
just not a Ratchet and Clank game,

354
00:18:17,393 --> 00:18:19,173
and definitely falls into the what were we thinking

355
00:18:19,213 --> 00:18:20,213
category of the franchise.

356
00:18:22,094 --> 00:18:23,914
So, you know, co-op was very well received,

357
00:18:23,994 --> 00:18:25,495
and the game was a commercial success,

358
00:18:25,955 --> 00:18:27,455
but the reviews were not as favorable.

359
00:18:27,835 --> 00:18:29,756
Deadlock received lower than expected scores,

360
00:18:29,796 --> 00:18:32,336
and even one reviewer called it soulless gun porn,

361
00:18:32,616 --> 00:18:33,217
which, that hurt.

362
00:18:33,237 --> 00:18:33,977
That's cold.

363
00:18:34,537 --> 00:18:34,797
I know.

364
00:18:35,457 --> 00:18:38,358
At the time, we had three huge successes behind us.

365
00:18:38,418 --> 00:18:39,838
We thought we could not fail.

366
00:18:41,239 --> 00:18:42,299
Now, looking back at the checklist

367
00:18:42,319 --> 00:18:43,639
that made Up Your Arsenal successful,

368
00:18:43,679 --> 00:18:45,680
it's easy to see why this was sort of a misstep for us.

369
00:18:46,103 --> 00:18:56,447
We had no engaging buddy story, our customizable weapon feature resulted in reduced personality, planetary exploration was gone, quark was left out of the fun, the color palette was muted, and we went overboard with the shooting.

370
00:18:56,987 --> 00:18:59,328
We even covered Ratchet's face for the majority of the game.

371
00:18:59,708 --> 00:19:03,929
Insomniac tried to make the game different, but in doing so, we swung the needle just a bit too far.

372
00:19:04,470 --> 00:19:07,711
It was clear that we had just deviated too far from the franchise DNA.

373
00:19:10,051 --> 00:19:12,032
Okay, so what do we mean when we say franchise DNA?

374
00:19:13,123 --> 00:19:16,826
These are the core pillars of the game from both a gameplay and lore perspective.

375
00:19:17,286 --> 00:19:20,989
No matter what you change from game to game, this is the stuff that stays constant so that

376
00:19:21,129 --> 00:19:23,490
each entry feels like it was made by a singular voice.

377
00:19:23,510 --> 00:19:26,552
It's one of those things you don't really think about until you see it done poorly,

378
00:19:26,652 --> 00:19:29,094
and then when it's done poorly, it really stands out.

379
00:19:30,235 --> 00:19:35,038
So we knew we had to return to what made previous games great, but also faced a new challenge

380
00:19:35,098 --> 00:19:37,139
on the horizon, which was the PlayStation 3.

381
00:19:38,335 --> 00:19:41,416
For this new platform, we needed to overhaul our engine and our tools.

382
00:19:41,476 --> 00:19:43,877
This meant we needed to build everything from the ground up.

383
00:19:43,897 --> 00:19:48,498
We couldn't reuse any of our characters, any of our sounds, any of our assets.

384
00:19:48,558 --> 00:19:50,099
We had to redo everything.

385
00:19:50,999 --> 00:19:54,040
So this was a big technology upheaval for us.

386
00:19:54,740 --> 00:19:58,221
This is common to most franchises that span multiple platforms.

387
00:19:58,421 --> 00:20:02,382
Anyone, of course, who's worked in the industry for a few years knows this happens quite a

388
00:20:02,422 --> 00:20:04,143
bit where you have to kind of do a retooling.

389
00:20:05,583 --> 00:20:05,723
So...

390
00:20:06,702 --> 00:20:08,483
We had promised with Tools of Destruction, though,

391
00:20:08,503 --> 00:20:11,205
that we were going to make this CG animated movie,

392
00:20:11,265 --> 00:20:13,846
or it was going to feel like you could play a CG animated movie.

393
00:20:14,886 --> 00:20:16,507
And I started to get really caught up

394
00:20:16,567 --> 00:20:19,729
in the allure of what the PlayStation 3 could do.

395
00:20:19,769 --> 00:20:21,610
And I was thinking about, oh, maybe there

396
00:20:21,630 --> 00:20:25,712
could be procedural worlds, or we could have multiplayer modes.

397
00:20:25,732 --> 00:20:28,693
We could have this open space exploration.

398
00:20:28,713 --> 00:20:32,655
And I started chatting about this in one of the design

399
00:20:32,695 --> 00:20:33,035
meetings.

400
00:20:33,714 --> 00:20:36,917
And a team member decided, walked up to the whiteboard

401
00:20:37,257 --> 00:20:41,541
and wrote in giant letters, technology is evil.

402
00:20:43,283 --> 00:20:46,125
And so he was coming from having worked

403
00:20:46,246 --> 00:20:48,848
on our other PlayStation 3 game, which was a launch title,

404
00:20:48,908 --> 00:20:50,409
which was Resistance Fall of Man.

405
00:20:50,850 --> 00:20:53,092
And that game had a ton of ambitious systems.

406
00:20:53,132 --> 00:20:53,632
We had like.

407
00:20:54,218 --> 00:21:00,603
procedural glass and cloth and like hoses and crazy AI systems.

408
00:21:01,063 --> 00:21:02,704
And we managed to get glass into that game,

409
00:21:02,724 --> 00:21:05,045
but everything else, a lot of other stuff had to get cut.

410
00:21:06,026 --> 00:21:08,988
Because in the end, you have to really be careful

411
00:21:09,008 --> 00:21:10,309
when you're starting with new tech.

412
00:21:10,569 --> 00:21:12,210
There's just, it can be a lot of rope

413
00:21:12,250 --> 00:21:14,011
that you end up hanging yourselves with.

414
00:21:14,812 --> 00:21:15,712
The glass was great, though.

415
00:21:15,812 --> 00:21:16,633
The glass was great.

416
00:21:17,493 --> 00:21:22,176
So given that we had to rewrite our new engine and tools,

417
00:21:22,216 --> 00:21:23,697
this meant a smaller scope.

418
00:21:25,216 --> 00:21:30,981
And so we had fewer cinematics just because of the higher fidelity animation.

419
00:21:31,681 --> 00:21:39,288
There was no multiplayer or co-op, no spherical worlds, and no fun stuff like racing or other special modes.

420
00:21:39,548 --> 00:21:41,710
We had to really go lean on this one.

421
00:21:42,430 --> 00:21:47,935
So we were wondering, how do we please long-time fans if the graphics were taking a step forward

422
00:21:47,975 --> 00:21:50,657
and our gameplay and story breadth was taking a step back?

423
00:21:51,571 --> 00:21:54,172
We needed to go lean and deep on our franchise DNA,

424
00:21:54,232 --> 00:21:55,312
but where to start?

425
00:21:56,853 --> 00:22:00,094
So the answer for us was to tell a tightly told story

426
00:22:00,174 --> 00:22:01,955
about Ratchet and Clank's origins.

427
00:22:02,355 --> 00:22:04,156
Rather than following the fly by the seat of our pants

428
00:22:04,196 --> 00:22:06,076
approach as we did with our previous games,

429
00:22:06,457 --> 00:22:08,217
we needed to start thinking about world building.

430
00:22:08,677 --> 00:22:10,218
That's what we brought on TJ.

431
00:22:11,258 --> 00:22:13,019
I've been working on games for a couple years by then,

432
00:22:13,059 --> 00:22:15,520
doing QA and design support on Resistance Fall of Man.

433
00:22:16,200 --> 00:22:17,481
And I also come out to LA at the time

434
00:22:17,521 --> 00:22:18,361
to build up a writing career,

435
00:22:18,381 --> 00:22:19,922
but I had never written a video game before.

436
00:22:20,365 --> 00:22:22,306
that was coming on board several months into production.

437
00:22:24,027 --> 00:22:26,227
And one of my chief duties was to take the sort of loose

438
00:22:26,267 --> 00:22:29,109
mythology of Ratchet and Clank and work with this guy and

439
00:22:29,129 --> 00:22:32,110
Brian Hastings to build out a unified lore that could inform

440
00:22:32,170 --> 00:22:34,370
future games, as well as comics and movies.

441
00:22:34,751 --> 00:22:36,791
Around this time, stories were starting to matter more in the

442
00:22:36,831 --> 00:22:39,392
gaming space, so we really knew that we had to step it up.

443
00:22:39,892 --> 00:22:42,513
We had a great set of characters and planets, but the

444
00:22:42,613 --> 00:22:46,195
original lore was done 100% on the fly and had to be tied

445
00:22:46,235 --> 00:22:48,636
down so that we could satisfy some of the audience's

446
00:22:48,756 --> 00:22:49,476
pressing questions.

447
00:22:50,258 --> 00:22:52,900
Here's a horrifying list of things that we did not have the answers to.

448
00:22:54,201 --> 00:22:54,882
Who is Ratchet?

449
00:22:55,863 --> 00:22:56,423
Simple, right?

450
00:22:56,443 --> 00:22:59,165
Beyond just guns and wisecracks. I believe it or not, we didn't know.

451
00:22:59,506 --> 00:23:01,928
We knew the surface-y stuff, like what made him fun,

452
00:23:02,028 --> 00:23:04,230
but what about all the writer-y stuff that I like to talk about

453
00:23:04,250 --> 00:23:05,891
to make programmers' eyes glaze over?

454
00:23:06,411 --> 00:23:08,033
What drives him? What's he afraid of?

455
00:23:08,073 --> 00:23:10,515
I love that Ratchet was a wide-eyed engineer

456
00:23:10,835 --> 00:23:13,798
who prioritized fun and thrills over basic safety protocol,

457
00:23:14,118 --> 00:23:16,119
but the earlier games never really explored why.

458
00:23:16,580 --> 00:23:16,940
And to me...

459
00:23:17,858 --> 00:23:19,680
Gratchet is constantly struggling with his identity

460
00:23:19,720 --> 00:23:22,182
because he was born an orphan and the only Lombex

461
00:23:22,222 --> 00:23:22,962
as far as he knew.

462
00:23:23,443 --> 00:23:24,764
So his need to invent came from his need

463
00:23:24,784 --> 00:23:26,505
to feel like he had an impact on the universe.

464
00:23:27,046 --> 00:23:29,007
Building on this vulnerability helped us create

465
00:23:29,027 --> 00:23:30,949
a more textured character that players could relate to.

466
00:23:32,950 --> 00:23:33,871
Where are the Lombexes?

467
00:23:34,631 --> 00:23:36,833
I would love to tell you all that we had this mapped out

468
00:23:36,953 --> 00:23:39,555
in a Bible like in Underlock and Key of the Insomniac Vault,

469
00:23:39,595 --> 00:23:40,676
but we had no idea.

470
00:23:41,517 --> 00:23:42,597
It was White Space at the time.

471
00:23:42,998 --> 00:23:45,039
Fans were dying to know what happened to the other Lombexes

472
00:23:45,340 --> 00:23:47,141
and we wanted to address this in the new trilogy.

473
00:23:49,280 --> 00:23:49,920
Who is Clank?

474
00:23:51,100 --> 00:23:53,281
The original game featured him as a factory defect

475
00:23:53,301 --> 00:23:54,221
that escaped the junk heap.

476
00:23:54,581 --> 00:23:55,801
But over the course of four games,

477
00:23:55,841 --> 00:23:57,702
the studio felt like there had to be more to him.

478
00:23:58,342 --> 00:23:59,582
Brian Hastings asked me to come up

479
00:23:59,602 --> 00:24:02,403
with a reveal for him that would shed new light on his origins

480
00:24:02,443 --> 00:24:04,103
without hopefully feeling too retconned.

481
00:24:04,783 --> 00:24:06,223
And during one of our brainstorming meetings

482
00:24:06,283 --> 00:24:07,624
on Tools Destruction, the team was

483
00:24:07,664 --> 00:24:10,104
very excited about time manipulation as a mechanic.

484
00:24:10,684 --> 00:24:12,645
So we developed a connection between Clank

485
00:24:12,685 --> 00:24:14,985
and a faction of time-bending creatures called the Zoni.

486
00:24:15,465 --> 00:24:17,106
And at the time, I had a vague idea

487
00:24:17,326 --> 00:24:18,306
of how he was connected to them.

488
00:24:18,575 --> 00:24:21,577
but felt that this could tee up a compelling origin story

489
00:24:21,597 --> 00:24:22,718
to be revealed in a future game.

490
00:24:24,839 --> 00:24:26,220
And there was so much more we didn't know.

491
00:24:26,321 --> 00:24:28,622
These are all questions fans wanted the answers to.

492
00:24:29,003 --> 00:24:31,324
And even though we were going to a new galaxy in a future saga,

493
00:24:31,665 --> 00:24:33,606
I had to start compiling a franchise Bible

494
00:24:33,646 --> 00:24:35,307
so that every team had a place to start.

495
00:24:35,628 --> 00:24:37,469
And I had to get started halfway through production

496
00:24:37,769 --> 00:24:39,991
when all our sets were built, our characters were modeled,

497
00:24:40,251 --> 00:24:41,412
levels were already locked down.

498
00:24:41,832 --> 00:24:44,634
So this was truly trial by fire for a first time game writer.

499
00:24:45,415 --> 00:24:47,056
You like to throw people into the frying pan sometimes.

500
00:24:47,076 --> 00:24:47,396
Yes, you do.

501
00:24:48,895 --> 00:24:53,776
And once we hit alpha, it became very clear that we didn't have the time or the resources to answer everything.

502
00:24:54,136 --> 00:24:57,057
So I had to prioritize while laying the groundwork for the next game.

503
00:24:57,377 --> 00:24:59,777
That way fans could feel secure knowing that the answers were coming.

504
00:25:00,378 --> 00:25:01,958
I like to call these mythology branches,

505
00:25:02,178 --> 00:25:05,339
fleshing out your world with details that serve as flavor in one game,

506
00:25:05,659 --> 00:25:06,999
but can be a full meal the next.

507
00:25:07,379 --> 00:25:09,860
So the Zoni, Terracnoid Sages, the Court of Azimuth,

508
00:25:09,900 --> 00:25:13,381
as well as other terms that might sound like gobbledygook if you haven't played the series,

509
00:25:13,841 --> 00:25:15,962
these concepts were seeded in Tools Destruction.

510
00:25:16,462 --> 00:25:19,063
without knowing exactly how they would be used going forward.

511
00:25:19,883 --> 00:25:22,204
But when we paid it off, it provided a sense of continuity

512
00:25:22,624 --> 00:25:25,185
and the illusion of a plan that I definitely did not have.

513
00:25:25,625 --> 00:25:25,925
Cheers.

514
00:25:26,785 --> 00:25:27,585
I thought he had a plan.

515
00:25:27,665 --> 00:25:28,426
Yeah, no, no, no.

516
00:25:28,646 --> 00:25:29,146
Heavy fold.

517
00:25:30,686 --> 00:25:31,666
So what did we learn from all this?

518
00:25:31,887 --> 00:25:33,287
If writers do their jobs right,

519
00:25:33,307 --> 00:25:35,548
the audience will engage with and comb over

520
00:25:36,068 --> 00:25:37,848
every crumb of lore they're offered.

521
00:25:38,548 --> 00:25:40,469
It's the double-edged sword of good mythology work.

522
00:25:40,789 --> 00:25:42,610
They'll look for cracks and continuity errors.

523
00:25:42,890 --> 00:25:45,290
They'll create fan-made wikis to point out every consistency.

524
00:25:45,720 --> 00:25:51,363
So keep in mind, make sure not to define heroes by a game mechanic.

525
00:25:51,423 --> 00:25:54,644
Find something emotional and relatable about them, something that they're missing.

526
00:25:54,804 --> 00:25:57,145
Audiences want to see themselves in their heroes.

527
00:25:58,046 --> 00:26:00,867
And that's going to give your character the kind of depth you'll need to carry them

528
00:26:00,927 --> 00:26:04,088
over the next two or three, or in our case, seven games.

529
00:26:04,989 --> 00:26:08,630
White space is okay, but nail down the critical aspects of your lore.

530
00:26:10,431 --> 00:26:12,712
Use mythology branches to tee up a larger world.

531
00:26:13,632 --> 00:26:15,372
Be specific about those aspects.

532
00:26:15,672 --> 00:26:17,693
No ambiguity, because ambiguity can oftentimes

533
00:26:17,753 --> 00:26:19,494
read like plot holes or an unsure writer.

534
00:26:19,874 --> 00:26:22,515
And consider whatever you write, law going forward.

535
00:26:23,975 --> 00:26:25,275
Write for the hardcore gamer.

536
00:26:25,836 --> 00:26:28,156
When you're deep in crunch, it's very easy to say,

537
00:26:28,316 --> 00:26:29,357
people won't notice.

538
00:26:30,137 --> 00:26:33,278
But the hardcore do, I promise you, they always do.

539
00:26:33,978 --> 00:26:35,739
They will YouTube it, they will Wiki it,

540
00:26:35,819 --> 00:26:37,420
they will tweet it at you angrily.

541
00:26:37,440 --> 00:26:39,980
They will evangelize or eviscerate your work.

542
00:26:40,060 --> 00:26:42,421
I've had both done, and I can give you a guess

543
00:26:42,481 --> 00:26:43,321
as to which one is better.

544
00:26:45,775 --> 00:26:47,756
Putting in the work benefits not only the team,

545
00:26:47,816 --> 00:26:49,837
but future partners and ancillary products

546
00:26:49,878 --> 00:26:50,658
based on your series.

547
00:26:52,979 --> 00:26:56,321
So, by doing all that work and defining the mythology,

548
00:26:56,341 --> 00:26:57,742
it just gave us a great foundation

549
00:26:57,802 --> 00:26:59,483
for building these worlds and adventures

550
00:27:00,243 --> 00:27:02,144
that are for our upcoming trilogy.

551
00:27:02,884 --> 00:27:04,045
But as new designers joined the team,

552
00:27:04,085 --> 00:27:06,786
we realized we could not solely rely on oral tradition.

553
00:27:07,967 --> 00:27:10,268
Over the six years, we had people leaving,

554
00:27:10,328 --> 00:27:11,569
coming in, new designers.

555
00:27:12,154 --> 00:27:16,755
And so we had to start figuring out how do we develop a rat and,

556
00:27:16,995 --> 00:27:19,695
sorry, ah, ratchet and clank and standardize our process.

557
00:27:20,415 --> 00:27:24,316
One thing that came up, which was kind of wild, was we had these crate stacks.

558
00:27:24,396 --> 00:27:26,857
And for a lot of us working on the early games,

559
00:27:26,877 --> 00:27:28,657
some of this was pretty intuitive on how to place them.

560
00:27:29,217 --> 00:27:33,418
But some of our new designers would either put these giant stacks,

561
00:27:33,478 --> 00:27:35,838
and people would just start getting tired of pressing the square button,

562
00:27:35,878 --> 00:27:38,959
like hitting all of those crates, or they'd have very sparse stacks

563
00:27:38,979 --> 00:27:40,979
that wouldn't quite be stacked correctly.

564
00:27:41,478 --> 00:27:49,341
So Brian Hastings, our creative officer, actually wrote a four-page document on how to stack crates.

565
00:27:49,721 --> 00:27:51,442
The subtle art of crate-crafting.

566
00:27:51,462 --> 00:27:53,582
Yeah, it was pretty in-depth. It was impressive.

567
00:27:56,143 --> 00:28:01,385
So, of course, one of the most important processes that we had to standardize was how to design great weapons.

568
00:28:01,865 --> 00:28:08,087
On Deadlocked, we had this really cool feature, which was you could create customizable weapons in various combinations.

569
00:28:08,530 --> 00:28:11,993
but they started to kind of lose a little bit of their soul and personality.

570
00:28:12,953 --> 00:28:13,874
So we thought, well, you know,

571
00:28:13,894 --> 00:28:16,996
what are some general guidelines or goals that we could use while

572
00:28:17,096 --> 00:28:19,437
brainstorming weapons? And so we threw out three.

573
00:28:20,158 --> 00:28:24,100
One is they had to be comedic, strategic, or spectacle.

574
00:28:24,120 --> 00:28:27,302
And they had to hit a 10 in one of those categories.

575
00:28:27,963 --> 00:28:31,665
And so this actually helped us in developing a one of our favorite weapons,

576
00:28:31,845 --> 00:28:32,586
Mr. Zircon.

577
00:28:33,932 --> 00:28:37,833
where originally he was designed as being a Synthenoid,

578
00:28:37,873 --> 00:28:39,834
which was a character we'd had in earlier games

579
00:28:39,874 --> 00:28:41,994
where it was a fire and forget drone

580
00:28:42,014 --> 00:28:44,075
that would kind of hover above you and just shoot at enemies.

581
00:28:44,135 --> 00:28:45,515
And they were kind of fun to have,

582
00:28:45,555 --> 00:28:47,556
but we thought, how do we step this guy up?

583
00:28:47,636 --> 00:28:50,437
And we started building this character,

584
00:28:50,457 --> 00:28:51,917
and he looked like one of these consumer bots

585
00:28:51,997 --> 00:28:54,058
on the left here and had very little personality.

586
00:28:54,118 --> 00:28:56,818
And we're like, okay, there's no strategy here.

587
00:28:57,078 --> 00:28:58,659
It's not really much spectacle,

588
00:28:58,819 --> 00:29:01,760
but we can certainly push it in terms of the comedy factor.

589
00:29:02,334 --> 00:29:06,038
So I asked the art team if we could give him a mouth.

590
00:29:06,118 --> 00:29:07,319
I walked over to TJ, I'm like,

591
00:29:07,339 --> 00:29:09,081
hey, we got this guy named Mr. Zircon.

592
00:29:09,481 --> 00:29:11,383
He speaks in the third person, go.

593
00:29:12,384 --> 00:29:13,965
This is not the kind of request

594
00:29:13,985 --> 00:29:15,307
you want to get during crunch time.

595
00:29:16,388 --> 00:29:17,529
But I understood Brian's vision.

596
00:29:17,569 --> 00:29:18,790
I agree with him that it was important.

597
00:29:18,830 --> 00:29:20,872
So I came up with what, in hindsight,

598
00:29:20,912 --> 00:29:23,615
looked on paper to be the dumbest idea for a character ever.

599
00:29:23,635 --> 00:29:26,297
I wondered if Mr. Zircon loved to talk trash

600
00:29:26,317 --> 00:29:27,658
but just happened to be really terrible at it.

601
00:29:28,604 --> 00:29:29,884
He thought everything around him was stupid.

602
00:29:30,005 --> 00:29:31,485
He had no inflection in his voice,

603
00:29:31,545 --> 00:29:33,166
and he lived only to kill what was around him.

604
00:29:33,587 --> 00:29:36,708
So in a couple days, I whipped up 400 lines of VO

605
00:29:37,069 --> 00:29:38,450
and took it to the team, and they looked at me

606
00:29:38,490 --> 00:29:39,350
like I was insane.

607
00:29:40,151 --> 00:29:41,811
But when we recorded it, got into the game,

608
00:29:41,832 --> 00:29:44,013
and balanced it, it worked, and it became

609
00:29:44,073 --> 00:29:46,194
one of the most iconic character gadgets

610
00:29:46,234 --> 00:29:47,215
in Ratchet and Clank history.

611
00:29:48,335 --> 00:29:50,397
Yeah, I think it's all because we had those goals

612
00:29:50,477 --> 00:29:52,398
early on on how to push all these weapons

613
00:29:52,418 --> 00:29:53,238
and bring them up to a 10.

614
00:29:54,100 --> 00:29:57,023
So one of the weapons that was a big favor, of course,

615
00:29:57,063 --> 00:30:00,005
was the Groovitron, which was a weapon that makes enemies dance.

616
00:30:00,726 --> 00:30:02,067
And it's interesting.

617
00:30:02,087 --> 00:30:04,829
When we started to have that way of evaluating our weapons,

618
00:30:04,849 --> 00:30:06,110
we looked back at this weapon, and we

619
00:30:06,150 --> 00:30:07,711
realized why it was so successful.

620
00:30:07,751 --> 00:30:09,532
It actually hit all three of those goals.

621
00:30:10,033 --> 00:30:10,934
It was hilarious.

622
00:30:11,954 --> 00:30:14,536
It also had this big spectacle with all these beams coming out,

623
00:30:14,576 --> 00:30:15,697
all these enemies dancing.

624
00:30:15,717 --> 00:30:16,998
And it was a very strategic weapon.

625
00:30:17,038 --> 00:30:21,021
You could toss it out, and it was like an AoE stun weapon.

626
00:30:24,833 --> 00:30:29,556
So as part of our return to form on Tools of Destruction, of course, we brought back one of our signature levels,

627
00:30:29,576 --> 00:30:31,657
which was Metropolis or Aliro City.

628
00:30:32,498 --> 00:30:37,101
And this time it was featured in stunning detail with enemy fire raining down.

629
00:30:38,722 --> 00:30:41,504
Ratchet & Clank Tools of Destruction was a big hit with fans.

630
00:30:41,564 --> 00:30:46,727
It was often praised as looking like a Pixar film and hit all of the key ingredients of our DNA.

631
00:30:47,147 --> 00:30:51,350
In terms of story, it both answered and raised many questions about Ratchet & Clank's origins.

632
00:30:53,051 --> 00:30:56,452
But the game's cliffhanger ending left people feeling a bit cheated.

633
00:30:56,472 --> 00:30:59,554
And if I was to do it over again, I probably would not have done it.

634
00:31:00,734 --> 00:31:03,195
Sure, cliffhangers can be appealing, and I think used appropriately,

635
00:31:03,235 --> 00:31:05,236
they are an effective way of retaining audience interest.

636
00:31:05,256 --> 00:31:08,817
But I think oftentimes it just ends up leaving players feeling frustrated.

637
00:31:08,837 --> 00:31:13,299
Yeah, essentially, you know, Clank got abducted by the Zoni,

638
00:31:13,339 --> 00:31:16,100
and nobody knew what happened to him, so players were left...

639
00:31:16,850 --> 00:31:17,990
hanging with this question.

640
00:31:18,370 --> 00:31:20,711
And we really wanted to address this cliffhanger,

641
00:31:20,751 --> 00:31:22,612
but our problem was that the next game

642
00:31:22,632 --> 00:31:23,592
was gonna be in a couple years,

643
00:31:23,612 --> 00:31:25,193
and we didn't know if people could wait that long.

644
00:31:26,513 --> 00:31:29,634
But fortunately, we received both a blessing and a curse

645
00:31:29,754 --> 00:31:33,115
in the form of a, that's my fancy PowerPoint transition

646
00:31:33,135 --> 00:31:35,276
there, development curveballs.

647
00:31:36,356 --> 00:31:39,017
And so all projects face these, we're out of the blue,

648
00:31:39,037 --> 00:31:41,458
there's a particular request, the publisher asks

649
00:31:41,498 --> 00:31:44,579
for something, or some tech change happens.

650
00:31:45,184 --> 00:31:49,828
And during Tools of Destruction, what happened with us was we originally wanted to do a co-op,

651
00:31:49,988 --> 00:31:55,173
have a co-op feature, and be able to play the campaign with split screen or potentially online.

652
00:31:55,893 --> 00:31:59,977
And we talked to Sony about this, we promised it, and then about midway through, I think we were

653
00:32:00,017 --> 00:32:04,660
like, yeah, that's not going to happen, sorry. So the deal we ended up making was like, well,

654
00:32:04,700 --> 00:32:11,906
now we'll make a smaller product instead, and would come out in 2008 between Tools of Destruction

655
00:32:12,087 --> 00:32:14,268
and A Crack in Time, which was the next big installment.

656
00:32:15,607 --> 00:32:20,689
So, you know, that was DLC at the time, it was like this brand new concept,

657
00:32:21,369 --> 00:32:26,992
and we were pretty excited about working on this, but unfortunately it would eat a lot into our pre-production time.

658
00:32:27,452 --> 00:32:30,654
So for a while we had a bit of a freak-out moment,

659
00:32:32,094 --> 00:32:37,077
and we realized, though, that we could turn this obstacle into an opportunity.

660
00:32:37,637 --> 00:32:40,938
With a smaller game we could experiment with new ideas and new mechanics.

661
00:32:41,908 --> 00:32:43,769
and they could potentially lead into future games.

662
00:32:43,929 --> 00:32:46,351
And one idea that was starting to gain traction

663
00:32:46,411 --> 00:32:49,072
was doing this 2D space combat game

664
00:32:49,672 --> 00:32:51,013
that was similar to Geometry Wars

665
00:32:51,033 --> 00:32:53,335
because that was kind of the flavor of the month.

666
00:32:54,355 --> 00:32:56,516
But then we thought, well, we've got this cliffhanger.

667
00:32:56,556 --> 00:32:58,718
We kind of want to continue Ratchet and Clank's story.

668
00:32:59,038 --> 00:33:00,278
T.G. was getting hate mail.

669
00:33:00,619 --> 00:33:03,700
So maybe we should, you know, focus more on the story.

670
00:33:03,840 --> 00:33:06,462
And the one thing we really loved about the previous game

671
00:33:06,482 --> 00:33:08,923
that we wanted to do was Space Pirates.

672
00:33:09,204 --> 00:33:10,784
I mean, those are just awesome.

673
00:33:11,045 --> 00:33:11,145
And...

674
00:33:12,653 --> 00:33:14,334
So that's how Quest for Booty was born.

675
00:33:14,494 --> 00:33:17,796
It's actually the title that we originally wanted to come with,

676
00:33:17,836 --> 00:33:22,179
Tools of Destruction, but it worked much better for this smaller pirate-based game.

677
00:33:22,759 --> 00:33:25,060
And we really loved pirates at the time.

678
00:33:25,120 --> 00:33:30,724
We actually started to decorate the office with pirate flags, we had pirate skulls.

679
00:33:30,744 --> 00:33:32,965
We felt like the little band off in the corner,

680
00:33:34,006 --> 00:33:36,127
making this crazy little experimental game.

681
00:33:37,639 --> 00:33:40,240
But, you know, we could leverage all of the stuff we had from tools of destruction, but

682
00:33:40,260 --> 00:33:42,881
this also gave us the opportunity to start experimenting.

683
00:33:43,101 --> 00:33:47,163
And we came up with this idea for this wrench tether gadget where the head of the wrench

684
00:33:47,183 --> 00:33:49,785
would detach and latch onto bolts and you could kind of pull them down.

685
00:33:49,805 --> 00:33:54,627
And it was really a new concept for platforming and puzzles.

686
00:33:55,868 --> 00:34:00,930
We had, you could also pick up flaming lava rocks with it and throw them off of grind

687
00:34:00,990 --> 00:34:01,330
rails.

688
00:34:01,770 --> 00:34:06,473
And we had this really cool open island that you could freely explore with these towers.

689
00:34:08,936 --> 00:34:12,900
We also had several NPCs that Ransom could talk to and experiment with conversation trees.

690
00:34:13,180 --> 00:34:18,344
We wanted to see how far we can get, pushing features that you often find in RPG-style adventure games.

691
00:34:21,547 --> 00:34:27,112
Now to address the cliffhanger, we used this game as an opportunity to reveal the identity of the villain who kidnapped Clank.

692
00:34:27,212 --> 00:34:31,175
We used Dr. Nefarious. Fans had been clamoring for his return ever since Up Your Arsenal,

693
00:34:31,516 --> 00:34:36,080
and bringing him back felt like a great way to build out our universe, which now spans something like three galaxies.

694
00:34:37,722 --> 00:34:39,843
So we saw a lot of positives with this project.

695
00:34:40,543 --> 00:34:42,344
We developed, of course, the new wrench mechanic.

696
00:34:43,244 --> 00:34:45,405
It was like one of our biggest returns on investment,

697
00:34:45,425 --> 00:34:46,886
even though that investment was pretty small.

698
00:34:47,046 --> 00:34:48,847
It's cool to see that it's still making money.

699
00:34:50,267 --> 00:34:53,148
And it was, for me, actually one of the most enjoyable games

700
00:34:53,168 --> 00:34:54,949
to work on, given its small scope.

701
00:34:54,989 --> 00:34:56,690
It had much fewer headaches.

702
00:34:57,991 --> 00:35:01,412
In terms of, oops, sorry.

703
00:35:02,690 --> 00:35:08,753
In terms of negatives, our Metacritic was actually one of the lowest ones I think Insomniac ever got, which was 75 at the time.

704
00:35:09,934 --> 00:35:19,620
It was three to four hours long, people complained about the length, no weapon upgrades, there was no cork, and then we had this teapot matter, which I like to call teapot gates.

705
00:35:21,641 --> 00:35:28,205
At one point in the game, you're traveling around this level I believe we called Marl Caverns with a decapitated space pirate's head on a stick.

706
00:35:29,243 --> 00:35:33,644
And he would walk around, he would talk as you're walking from room to room, and I thought it would be funny

707
00:35:34,204 --> 00:35:37,224
if he just sang I'm a little teapot in order to open one of the doors.

708
00:35:37,264 --> 00:35:41,245
It was just one of those dumb, funny jokes that you'd throw in without thinking a lot about it.

709
00:35:41,705 --> 00:35:47,166
It turns out someone actually owns the rights to I'm a little teapot, and that person has lawyers.

710
00:35:48,126 --> 00:35:52,727
So they got involved, and it actually became Teapotgate.

711
00:35:52,907 --> 00:35:56,808
So the bonus tip here is don't ever assume that a nursery rhyme is public domain.

712
00:35:58,063 --> 00:36:00,545
I was actually thinking of playing the clip, but we probably shouldn't.

713
00:36:00,585 --> 00:36:00,885
Yeah.

714
00:36:03,146 --> 00:36:06,827
Okay, so for that game, we adopted this why not mindset.

715
00:36:07,968 --> 00:36:11,310
You know, we really wanted to turn our curveball into an opportunity.

716
00:36:11,370 --> 00:36:12,130
We felt like we did.

717
00:36:12,430 --> 00:36:14,531
It gave us a chance to really flesh out our universe.

718
00:36:15,631 --> 00:36:20,274
It really helps, you know, experimentation we find helps lead to future breakthroughs.

719
00:36:21,583 --> 00:36:24,725
you really need to kind of do these on the heels of a success.

720
00:36:25,185 --> 00:36:28,607
Had we done this after Deadlock, that probably would not have been a wise choice.

721
00:36:28,627 --> 00:36:32,850
Of course, smaller, cheaper games have lower stakes as well.

722
00:36:33,230 --> 00:36:36,732
So for our next game, it was Ratchet & Clank Future, A Crack in Time.

723
00:36:36,752 --> 00:36:38,693
A Crack in Time was my favorite,

724
00:36:39,133 --> 00:36:41,655
and it's still available at Holo game stores everywhere.

725
00:36:42,075 --> 00:36:42,715
Thanks for the plug.

726
00:36:44,536 --> 00:36:46,818
So we had less than a year to make our, um...

727
00:36:47,834 --> 00:36:51,998
biggest PlayStation 3 game because, you know, Quest for Booty again ate up a lot of our pre-production time.

728
00:36:52,878 --> 00:36:55,941
We really wanted this game to be great because we started to think that

729
00:36:56,822 --> 00:37:02,206
this was probably going to be the end of the trilogy, if not the franchise, and it was going to be our last and best

730
00:37:02,667 --> 00:37:03,387
Ratchet and Clank.

731
00:37:03,407 --> 00:37:08,131
Now at the start of the game we revealed that Clank had been taken by the Zoni

732
00:37:08,892 --> 00:37:12,535
to the Grey Clock, which had fallen under the control of Dr. Nefarious.

733
00:37:14,926 --> 00:37:16,687
We pull up the curtain back on Clank's origins,

734
00:37:16,747 --> 00:37:18,148
explaining his connection to the Zoni

735
00:37:18,248 --> 00:37:19,529
as heir apparent to the station.

736
00:37:19,549 --> 00:37:21,930
Rather than just being a defect,

737
00:37:21,970 --> 00:37:23,771
we reveal that Clank was destined to watch

738
00:37:23,871 --> 00:37:25,112
over the flow of time.

739
00:37:25,412 --> 00:37:30,335
And I hadn't even started watching Doctor Who yet, folks.

740
00:37:30,375 --> 00:37:31,876
We had Charles Martinet voice him,

741
00:37:32,056 --> 00:37:34,258
and meeting the guy who plays Mario

742
00:37:34,638 --> 00:37:36,439
was definitely a career highlight for me.

743
00:37:37,440 --> 00:37:39,321
I'm happy we don't have a picture of when I met him,

744
00:37:39,341 --> 00:37:40,782
because you would absolutely be able to tell

745
00:37:40,802 --> 00:37:41,862
from the look on his face

746
00:37:42,123 --> 00:37:43,303
that it was a career highlight for me.

747
00:37:45,996 --> 00:37:50,560
So Clank's story led us to develop a lot of special time puzzles where players could

748
00:37:51,220 --> 00:37:55,463
play and record multiple versions of Clank to solve these mind-bending puzzles.

749
00:37:56,724 --> 00:38:01,828
From our open world layout experimentation that we did in Quest for Booty, we actually

750
00:38:01,868 --> 00:38:05,391
developed this Krell Canyon level in A Crack in Time.

751
00:38:06,872 --> 00:38:08,934
And remember that mythology branch called the Court of Azimuth?

752
00:38:09,374 --> 00:38:13,498
Well, from that branch alone, we were inspired to create a Lombax character named Alistair

753
00:38:13,558 --> 00:38:13,878
Azimuth.

754
00:38:14,177 --> 00:38:19,219
It was a huge reveal for fans and it helped us answer a lot of questions I mentioned earlier about Ratchet's history and Lombax lore.

755
00:38:21,259 --> 00:38:26,641
We played off other mythology branches as well. The Trachnoid stages became a full-on faction in Kraken time.

756
00:38:29,062 --> 00:38:36,384
So this game was massive, even featuring space exploration, which is something that we really wish we could have done in previous games.

757
00:38:36,424 --> 00:38:41,126
We finally got to do it with this one. You could fly from planet to planet and engage in space battles.

758
00:38:41,700 --> 00:38:43,901
And even though our schedule was impossible,

759
00:38:43,921 --> 00:38:45,821
we kept piling more onto our plates for this one.

760
00:38:46,102 --> 00:38:47,662
So for example, there was this idea

761
00:38:47,682 --> 00:38:49,622
that was pitched to our team about space radio,

762
00:38:49,883 --> 00:38:51,123
where as you travel around the galaxy,

763
00:38:51,163 --> 00:38:52,563
you could actually listen to different stations.

764
00:38:52,603 --> 00:38:54,824
I think the audio guys were playing a lot of GTA at the time

765
00:38:55,524 --> 00:38:57,224
and it felt like something that could be really fun

766
00:38:57,264 --> 00:38:58,345
for Ratchet and Clank.

767
00:38:58,725 --> 00:39:00,125
But I had something like three days

768
00:39:00,185 --> 00:39:03,826
to write hours of commercials, DJ segues,

769
00:39:04,286 --> 00:39:05,607
banter, news broadcasts.

770
00:39:06,047 --> 00:39:08,447
Implementing it is, I'm told, a nightmare.

771
00:39:08,467 --> 00:39:09,668
The audio guys did it, not me.

772
00:39:10,651 --> 00:39:15,875
But this was an opportunity to build out our mythology and take one step closer to the feel of a living breathing universe.

773
00:39:15,995 --> 00:39:20,118
And everybody loved it. I think it ended up being one of the biggest selling points of the game.

774
00:39:20,859 --> 00:39:24,642
It's always a great sign when you're working on a project and it's kind of late in production.

775
00:39:24,702 --> 00:39:27,684
We feel like feature creeps have been hitting us pretty hard.

776
00:39:28,005 --> 00:39:32,748
And then you put in this other request, but everyone's really excited to make it happen and see the potential of it.

777
00:39:35,818 --> 00:39:38,659
So not only could you fly to these different planets, of course, you could visit these

778
00:39:38,719 --> 00:39:40,060
small spherical worlds.

779
00:39:40,460 --> 00:39:44,061
And this, of course, was something that we had developed in Going Commando.

780
00:39:45,041 --> 00:39:48,682
Around the same time, our animators were really hitting their stride in terms of making what

781
00:39:48,762 --> 00:39:51,063
felt like a feature-quality movie.

782
00:39:51,683 --> 00:39:53,003
I really hope this movie plays.

783
00:39:54,844 --> 00:39:55,024
Yes.

784
00:39:55,084 --> 00:39:55,364
All right.

785
00:39:55,404 --> 00:39:55,504
Quick!

786
00:39:55,524 --> 00:39:56,724
Everyone inside the temple!

787
00:39:56,744 --> 00:39:57,465
Ocelot is coming!

